About
Travellers Choice Best of the Best
2025
Rome has tons of epic fountains, but the Trevi Fountain is in a league of its own. Larger-than-life statues? Check. Cascades of water? You bet. A palace in the background? Absolutely. Top it all off with a seashell chariot driven by the god Oceanus, and youve got an aquatic wonderland thats been drawing crowds since 1762. If youve visited the Trevi in the past, you may find things a little more complicated than it used to be. With tourism spiking in recent years (including Romes 2025 Jubilee year), the city has made some changes geared toward both preserving the fountain and making the experience better. Youll still be able to see it just by walking through the Piazza di Trevi. But if you want to get close enough to throw in a coin, study the sculptures, or snap a pic, youll need to wait in line for a coveted front row spot.
Duration: 1-2 hours

Must-see highlights

  • Coins
    Stand with your back to the fountain and toss a coin over your left shoulderits good luck.
  • Statues
    The star here is Oceanus, god of the sea, who rides a seashell chariot pulled by horses.
  • Lights
    A new lighting system makes the fountain look spectacular at night (and even better in pics).
  • Acqua Vergine
    The underground aqueduct that powers so many of Romes fountains makes a stop here, too.
Things to know
  • Theres a long tradition of throwing three coins into the fountain: The first to return to Rome, the second to fall in love, and the third to get married.
  • Pro tip: Head to the second floor of the Benetton store across from the fountain for an excellent view.
  • Theres a second, hidden fountain off to the right if youre facing the Trevi: the Fountain of Lovers. Legend says couples who drink from it will stay in love forever. But maybe just toast with bottled water near the fountain instead; after all, it's the thoughtnot the fountain plumbingthat counts.
  • Keep your stuff close: The Trevi Fountain is famous for being a pickpocketing hot-spot.
Certainly the most famous and photographed fountain in Rome, legend has it that whoever throws a coin into the pond will return to Rome.

The area
Address
Neighbourhood: Trevi
A non-stop photo and souvenir opportunity, Trevi is all about action. From early morning through the wee hours, the piazza surrounding Trevi Fountain hosts a never-ending flow of tourists hoping to make a wish or take a selfie. Clever restaurants, charming gelaterias, uncanny bars, kitsch shops, and a range of hotels make up the local landscape. Beneath the bustle are the remains of an ancient neighbourhood that you can visit by heading over to a repertoire cinema and asking for a peek underground. There is something for everyone, but if peace and quiet are what you seek, plan to visit in the early morning hours.
How to get there
  • Barberini - Fontana di Trevi 7 min walk
  • Spagna 8 min walk
